  "prompt": "What is the Romeo and Juliet law?",
  "response": "The \"Romeo and Juliet\" law refers to legal statutes in various jurisdictions that provide certain protections for individuals who engage in consensual sexual relationships when one party is below the age of consent but close in age to the other party. These laws are intended to prevent the prosecution of young couples who are close in age from being labeled as sexual offenders due to minor age differences.\n\nTypically, these laws exist to address situations where two teenagers may engage in consensual sexual activity but where one or both parties are below the legal age of consent. The laws often have specific provisions that outline age differences that determine whether prosecution will occur. For example, in some jurisdictions, if the age difference is within a specific range (like two to four years), then the older party may not face criminal charges.\n\nIt's important to note that the specifics of Romeo and Juliet laws can vary significantly from state to state or country to country, so it is essential to understand the laws applicable in a particular jurisdiction.",
